6d4dea1e-ffa4-45cf-a9dd-9abf95cc3b79.0040a92b-4a49-4f89-9371-eb5220585370.description=
Runs a WMI query and formats the results.

Inputs\:
host - Host name or ip address of the system on which the WMI query will be run.
username - Username to use for WMI impersonation on the host for this operation (can be left blank).
password - Password of the user.
namespace - Namespace to run query against. If not provided, the root\cimv2 namespace is used by default.
query - The query to execute (e.g. select * from win32_service).
format - How to format the query's results (text or csv).

Responses\:
success - the operation succeeded.
failure - an error occurred.
6d4dea1e-ffa4-45cf-a9dd-9abf95cc3b79.1eb23086-2f2b-4c31-a340-401a0b63f721.description=
This operation uses WMI to attempt to create a remote process on target machine and run the command. 

Inputs\:
    host - Hostname or ip address of the target machine.
    command - The command you want to execute. Special characters\: '<', '>', '(', ')', '&' need to be escaped using the caret ('^') character.  The only exception to this rule is when the '>' character is used to redirect output.
    currentDirectory - The directory from which the command will be executed.
    user - Username to use for remote WMI impersonation and thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation (can be left blank).
    password - Password of the user.
    outputPath - Network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default the path will have to be changed on Windows 2000 systems.
    characterSet - The character encoding used to write the batch file that will be remotely executed by the operation. Unicode character encodings may not be supported for this input (utf-8, utf-16, etc.).  Support for unicode encodings depends on target system capabilities.  By default this encoding will also be used to read the command output that is redirected to temporary files.  If the command output is expected to be of different encoding, specify the different encoding in the "outputCharacterSet" input.  
Default value\: The encoding of the operating system where is RAS installed.
Examples\: ibm437, shift_jis
    outputCharacterSet - The character encoding used to read the command output that was redirected to temporary files.  Only need to specify this input if the output of the command is known to be of a different character encoding.  As an example\: the "wmic" command returns utf-16 encoded output.
Examples\: ibm437, shift_jis, utf-8, utf-16
    timeout - The number of seconds before assuming the remote process is no longer functional. After the timeout has expired the remote process and all child processes will be terminated.
Default value\: 600
    useDelegation - This input must be added by the user in order to be used. If set to "true" the operation will use the "Delegate" impersonation level and the "Kerberos" authentication protocol. If "false", empty or missing the operation will use "Impersonate" for the impersonation level and the default authentication protocol (which is NTLM).
Values\: true, false
Default\: false
    debugPath - This input must be added by the user in order to be used. If set to "true", an additional result field named "commandPassed" is returned and it contains the command that executes the script. For more information on the purpose of this input, see the "Notes" section.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It is the value from WMI for starting the process (not the exit value of the process).
    processID - The process id of the remote process.
    processReturnCode - The return code of the remote process.
    stdOut - Standard output from the remote process.
    stdErr - Standard error from the remote process.

Responses\:
    success - Remote process successfully launched and has completed executing.
    failure - Unable to start remote process.

Notes\: 
1. Internally this operation creates a temporary batch file with the following content\:

cmd /c " [command] 2> err.tmp 1> out.tmp "
echo %ERRORLEVEL% > ret.tmp

After the script is executed, the operation will read the files\: err.tmp (standard error), out.tmp (standard output) and ret.tmp (return code). Finally the operation deletes all the temporary files.
The command that executes the script can be accesed by adding a new input\: debugPath with the value\: "true"

2. List of possible encoding names (Support for the encoding may depend on the version or language of the RAS OS)\:
Encoding Name\:	Description\:
IBM437		OEM United States
DOS-720		Arabic (DOS)
ibm737		Greek (DOS)
ibm775		Baltic (DOS)

6d4dea1e-ffa4-45cf-a9dd-9abf95cc3b79.4b77ad54-0bcd-48dc-9af5-0108a61f791e.description=
Pings the target computer from a Windows host computer.

Input Parameters\:
host 		- The hostname or IP address of the host computer to ping from.
user 		- Username to use for remote WMI impersonation and thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation (can be left blank). The user to authenticate as.
password 		- Password of the user.
target 		- The target computer to ping.
packets 		- The number of packets to send to the target computer.
packetSize 		- The size of packets to send to the target computer.
command 		- DO NOT CHANGE THIS VALUE.
characterSet 	- The character encoding of the target computer. The default is RAS machine's default encoding.
outputPath 		- A network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible it should be changed to use another share that the local system account on the host computer has write-access to. By default, the path must be changed on Windows 2000 computers.

Responses\:
success 		- The target computer responded to all ping requests.
failure 		- The target computer did not respond to any ping request.
diagnosed		- The target computer responded only to some ping requests.
Connection Error	- The host computer could not be found or user credentials supplied to connect to it are incorrect.
Unknown Target	- The target computer could not be resolved to an IP address.

Result\:
The output of the ping operation.

Extra Results\:
returnResult		- The raw output of the Ping operation.
address 		- The actual IP address of the target computer.
% Packet Loss 	- The percentage of packets that ping replies were not received for.
average latency	- The average ping response time in milliseconds.
max latency 		- The maximum response time of all the ping reqeusts (in milliseconds).
min latency 		- The minimum number of milliseconds that was taken to receive a ping response.

Note\: If an encoding is not given by user, the batch file will be created using the RAS machine's default encoding,
That may cause to corruption in a case where remote machine's encoding is different than the RAS machine's one.
In that case,user must define the appropriate 'characterSet'
The character encoding specified in the input for characterSet must not be Unicode (ex. UTF-8, UTF-16).

6d4dea1e-ffa4-45cf-a9dd-9abf95cc3b79.8d53bd09-24e6-4e88-8e0e-bff526db34df.description=

Displays a message to the user.

Inputs\:
  message - The message text to display
  title - The title on the message window. Defaults to "Status message".

Responses\:
  Always returns success.

Examples\:
  In order to display the message "Finished" to the user, go to the 
  detail screen for the input named "message" and change the Otherwise option
  from Prompt User to Use Constant.  Then enter the text "Finished" into the
  Constant Value field.

  References to flow variables in the Contant Value field are expanded so that
  the text may be dynamic.  Flow variable references are of the form
  ${variable}.  For example, the text\:
     ${count} systems were modified 
  could be used to display a message about the number of systems that were
  repaired, whose value is in the flow variable "count".

  When the message is displayed, it will properly render any embedded html
  tags, which permits creating messages with more advanced formatting.  For 
  example to display a message in italics you could use\:
    This is important
  or to display a message in red\:
    This is really  important

  You can create messages that contain multiple lines by entering a multiple
  line message in the Constant Value field, or by using HTML 
 tags for line
  breaks.  Note that \n characters are displayed literally and are not used for
  creating multiple lines.
